docs.abstract: Two days in London on the world stage provided him no respite.
docs.snippet: Two days in London on the world stage provided him no respite.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When times turn tough, presidents can hop on Air Force One to escape the country for a while and stride purposefully across the world stage. But the world stage was not so friendly this week for President Trump, who landed back in Washington on Wednesday night to confront a grim couple of weeks ahead.

headline.main: Mocked Abroad and Assailed at Home, Trump Returns to Face Impeachment
headline.print_headline: Stung in Europe, and Finding No Balm at Home

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Iran has used the continuing chaos in Iraq to build up a hidden arsenal of short-range ballistic missiles in Iraq, part of a widening effort to try to intimidate the Middle East and assert its power, according to American intelligence and military officials.

docs.abstract: The 39th president was treated for a urinary tract infection, the latest of a series of health issues that he has endured in recent months.

docs.abstract: The law requires doctors to show and describe ultrasounds to women seeking abortions. Challengers said it violated the First Amendment.
docs.snippet: The law requires doctors to show and describe ultrasounds to women seeking abortions. Challengers said it violated the First Amendment.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court on Monday said it would not hear a challenge to a Kentucky law that requires doctors performing abortions to display fetal ultrasounds and to describe the images to women seeking the procedure. The court’s action means the law will go into effect.

headline.main: Supreme Court Lets Kentucky Abortion Ultrasound Law Take Effect
headline.print_headline: Abortion Ultrasound Law  To Take Effect in Kentucky

docs.abstract: The justices weighed whether the federal government may walk away from a commitment to shield insurance companies from losses.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court seemed inclined on Tuesday to require the federal government to live up to its promise to shield insurance companies from some of the risks they took in participating in the exchanges established by President Barack Obama’s health care law, the Affordable Care Act.

headline.main: Supreme Court May Back Insurers in $12 Billion Obamacare Case
headline.print_headline: Court Hears Insurers’ Suit on Federal Health Law

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration, brushing aside tens of thousands of protest letters, gave final approval on Wednesday to a rule that will remove nearly 700,000 people from the federal food-stamp program by strictly enforcing federal work requirements.
